var tafsirData_13 = {
  1: {
    "Alif-Lãm-Mĩm-Ra": "These are disconnected letters that appear at the beginning of some chapters of the Quran. Their exact meaning is known only to Allah. They serve to capture attention and demonstrate the miraculous nature of the Quran, which is composed of letters that humans use, yet they cannot produce anything like it.",
    "These are the verses of the Book": "This refers to the Quran, the divinely revealed scripture. Allah is drawing attention to the significance and authority of these verses, emphasizing that they are not ordinary words but divine communication sent to guide humanity.",
    "What has been revealed to you ˹O Prophet˺ from your Lord is the truth": "The message given to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) comes directly from Allah, the Lord and Sustainer. It is absolute truth with no falsehood in it whatsoever. This addresses those who doubted the authenticity of the revelation, confirming that it is genuinely from the Creator.",
    "but most people do not believe": "Despite the clear truth of this revelation, the majority of people reject it. This is not because the message is unclear, but because of their own stubbornness, arrogance, or blind following of their ancestors. Throughout history, most people have rejected divine guidance when it was sent to them, preferring their own desires over the truth."
  },
  2: {
    "It is Allah Who has raised the heavens without pillars—as you can see": "Look up at the sky and observe this magnificent sign. The vast heavens with all their stars, galaxies, and celestial bodies are suspended without any visible supports or columns holding them up. This is a display of Allah's infinite power that defies human comprehension. Just as a building needs pillars to stand, one would expect such an enormous structure to need support, yet Allah sustains it by His power alone.",
    "then established Himself on the Throne": "After creating the heavens and earth, Allah rose over His Throne in a manner that befits His majesty. The Throne is the greatest of all creations, and Allah's establishment over it signifies His absolute authority and sovereignty over all creation. We believe in this as Allah described it, without comparing it to anything in creation.",
    "He has subjected the sun and the moon, each orbiting for an appointed term": "Allah has made the sun and moon subservient, meaning they follow His commands precisely. They move in their orbits with exact timing, never deviating. This precise movement determines our days, nights, months, and years. They will continue this way until the Day of Judgment, which is their 'appointed term' when the current order of the universe will end.",
    "He conducts the whole affair": "Allah manages and controls every single matter in the universe, from the movement of galaxies to the growth of a single cell. Nothing happens without His knowledge and permission. He does not simply create and abandon; He actively sustains and directs all affairs at every moment.",
    "He makes the signs clear so that you may be certain of the meeting with your Lord": "Allah explains these signs of His power and creation in detail so that you may develop firm conviction that you will meet Him on the Day of Judgment. If Allah has the power to create and sustain such a magnificent universe, then resurrecting humans for accountability is certainly easy for Him. Reflecting on creation should lead to certainty about the afterlife."
  },
  3: {
    "And He is the One Who spread out the earth": "Allah extended and expanded the earth, making it spacious and suitable for habitation. Despite the earth being spherical, Allah made its surface appear spread out from the perspective of those living on it, allowing humans and creatures to settle, travel, build, and cultivate. This is a mercy and a sign of His perfect design.",
    "and placed firm mountains and rivers upon it": "Mountains serve as stabilizers for the earth, like pegs that prevent excessive shaking and movement. Rivers, meanwhile, provide fresh water that flows through the land, bringing life wherever they go. Both are essential for human survival—mountains provide minerals and water sources, while rivers enable agriculture, transportation, and sustenance.",
    "and created fruits of every kind in pairs": "Fruits come in pairs, whether referring to male and female plants needed for pollination, or varieties in taste, color, and characteristics—sweet and sour, large and small, different colors and textures. This diversity is not random; it is intentional design by the All-Wise Creator to provide variety and to demonstrate His creative power.",
    "He covers the day with night": "Allah causes the night to envelope and cover the day, creating a continuous cycle of light and darkness. This alternation allows for work during the day and rest at night. The transition between them is gradual and smooth, a mercy from Allah that maintains balance in nature and in human life.",
    "Surely in this are signs for those who reflect": "These aspects of creation—the spread earth, mountains, rivers, diverse fruits, and the cycle of day and night—are clear signs of Allah's existence, power, and wisdom. However, only those who contemplate and reflect deeply will recognize and appreciate these signs. Those who pass through life without thinking miss the profound messages embedded in creation."
  },
  4: {
    "And on the earth there are ˹different˺ neighbouring tracts": "Side by side on the same earth, you find vastly different types of land—fertile soil next to barren ground, rocky terrain beside lush valleys, salty land adjacent to sweet cultivable soil. These neighbouring pieces of land, though right next to each other, have completely different properties and produce different results.",
    "gardens of grapevines, ˹various˺ crops, palm trees—some stemming from the same root, others standing alone": "From the earth grow grapevines, various crops, and date palms. Some palm trees grow in clusters from a single root system, sharing the same base, while others stand individually. Despite coming from the same soil and root, they develop differently—a clear sign of Allah's creative will and power.",
    "They are all irrigated with the same water": "Here is the profound sign: all these different plants—grapes, crops, various types of palm trees—receive the same water. The rain falls equally on all, or they are watered from the same source. The water is identical, yet the results are astonishingly different.",
    "yet We make some taste better than others": "Despite receiving the same water from the same source in the same soil, some fruits turn out sweeter, some more flavorful, some more nutritious than others. This variation is not due to different inputs—it is Allah's direct intervention and design. He chooses to make some superior to others, demonstrating that He is the One controlling the outcome, not mere natural processes.",
    "Surely in this are signs for those who understand": "This phenomenon is a powerful proof for people who use their intellect. If nature alone determined outcomes, identical inputs would produce identical results. But they do not. This variation points to a Wise Creator who intentionally designs diversity and makes deliberate choices in His creation."
  },
  5: {
    "˹Now,˺ if anything should amaze you ˹O Prophet˺, then it is their question": "Allah is addressing the Prophet (peace be upon him), indicating that if there is something truly astonishing and worthy of wonder, it is the strange question these people ask. Their denial is so illogical given all the signs around them that it becomes the real source of amazement.",
    "\"When we are reduced to dust, will we really be raised as a new creation?\"": "The disbelievers found resurrection impossible to believe. They asked mockingly: after our bodies decompose and become dust, scattered and mixed with the earth, how could we possibly be brought back to life as new beings? They considered this beyond possibility, yet they ignored that the One who created them from nothing the first time can easily recreate them.",
    "It is they who have disbelieved in their Lord": "This denial of resurrection is essentially disbelief in Allah Himself. To deny that Allah can resurrect the dead is to deny His unlimited power. Such people have rejected their Lord, failing to recognize His ability over all things, despite witnessing His signs in creation daily.",
    "It is they who will have shackles around their necks": "On the Day of Judgment, these deniers will be bound with chains and shackles around their necks as a humiliation and punishment. The very resurrection they denied will occur, and they will face it in chains, unable to escape the reality they rejected.",
    "And it is they who will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever": "Their final abode is Hell, where they will remain eternally. This is the consequence of denying the meeting with their Lord and rejecting the message brought by His messenger. Their mockery of resurrection will turn into an everlasting reality of punishment."
  },
  6: {
    "They ask you ˹O Prophet˺ to hasten the torment rather than grace": "The disbelievers, in their arrogance and mockery, would challenge the Prophet by asking him to bring the punishment immediately if he was truly a messenger. Instead of seeking Allah's mercy and guidance, they sarcastically demanded the very punishment they were warned about, thinking it would never come.",
    "though there have ˹already˺ been ˹many˺ torments before them": "They spoke as if divine punishment was impossible, yet history is filled with examples of nations destroyed for their disbelief—the people of Noah drowned in the flood, the people of Lot destroyed by raining stones, Pharaoh and his army swallowed by the sea. These historical punishments should have served as warnings, but they ignored them.",
    "Surely your Lord is full of forgiveness for people, despite their wrongdoing": "Despite human beings constantly sinning and transgressing, Allah still forgives them abundantly. His mercy precedes His anger. If Allah were to punish people immediately for every sin, no one would survive. This patience and forgiveness is why punishment is delayed—giving people time to repent.",
    "and your Lord is truly severe in punishment": "However, Allah's mercy should not be mistaken for weakness or inability to punish. When His punishment comes, it is severe and inescapable. The delay in punishment is mercy, not inability. Those who persist in disbelief will eventually face a punishment they cannot bear. This verse balances hope in Allah's forgiveness with fear of His punishment."
  },
  7: {
    "The disbelievers say, \"If only a sign could be sent down to him from his Lord.\"": "The disbelievers demanded spectacular miracles according to their own wishes—perhaps splitting the moon, turning mountains into gold, or other dramatic displays. They used the absence of such miracles (as they defined them) as an excuse to reject the Prophet. However, the Quran itself was the greatest miracle, and numerous other signs were given, but those determined to disbelieve will always demand more.",
    "You ˹O Prophet˺ are only a warner": "Allah clarifies the Prophet's role—he is sent to warn people of the consequences of disbelief and to deliver the message clearly. He is not responsible for producing miracles on demand or forcing people to believe. His duty is to convey, not to compel, and certainly not to perform signs according to the whims of skeptics.",
    "And every people had a guide": "Every nation throughout history received a guide—a prophet or messenger—to show them the right path. This is Allah's justice; He does not punish people without first sending them clear guidance. Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) is the guide for his people and for all of humanity until the Day of Judgment."
  },
  8: {
    "Allah knows what every female bears": "Allah has complete knowledge of what every female creature carries in her womb—whether human or animal. He knows the gender, the physical features, the lifespan, the provision, and the destiny of every unborn being. Nothing about that creation is hidden from Him even before it takes form.",
    "and what increases and decreases in the wombs": "Allah knows every detail of pregnancy—the growth and development of the fetus, any decrease through miscarriage or complications, the exact timing of birth, whether there will be one child or multiple. Every biological process within the womb is known to Allah in complete detail, even what modern science cannot detect.",
    "And with Him everything is determined with precision": "Nothing in creation is random or accidental. Every single thing—from the orbit of planets to the number of leaves on a tree to the moments of a person's life—is measured and determined by Allah with exact precision. There is a divine wisdom and purpose behind every detail of existence."
  },
  9: {
    "˹He is the˺ Knower of the seen and the unseen": "Allah's knowledge encompasses everything—what is visible and observable to creation, and what is hidden and invisible. The unseen includes the future, the contents of hearts, the realm of angels and jinn, and everything beyond human perception. Nothing escapes His knowledge, whether apparent or concealed.",
    "the All-Great, Most Exalted": "Allah is the Greatest in every sense—in His essence, His attributes, and His actions. He is Most Exalted, above all of His creation, above any imperfection or deficiency. No matter how great anything in creation may seem, Allah is infinitely greater and higher."
  },
  10: {
    "It is the same ˹to Him˺ whether any of you speaks secretly or openly": "To Allah, there is no difference between what you whisper in private and what you announce publicly. Whether you speak in hushed tones so no one can hear, or shout for all to hear, Allah hears both equally well. No secret conversation is hidden from Him.",
    "whether one hides in the darkness of night or goes about in broad daylight": "Similarly, whether you conceal yourself in the darkest night, thinking no one can see you, or walk openly in the daylight, Allah sees you perfectly in both situations. The darkness that hides you from people does not hide you from Allah. This should make a believer conscious that Allah is always watching, in private and public, in darkness and light."
  },
  11: {
    "For each one there are successive angels before and behind, protecting them by Allah's command": "Every human being has angels assigned to them who take turns watching over them, some in front and some behind. These guardian angels protect the person from harm by Allah's permission. They accompany every individual, recording deeds and providing protection according to what Allah has decreed. This protection continues as long as Allah wills it.",
    "Indeed, Allah would never change a people's state ˹of favour˺ until they change their own state ˹of faith˺": "This is a profound principle of divine justice. Allah does not remove blessings, security, prosperity, or well-being from a people unless they themselves change—abandoning gratitude for ingratitude, obedience for disobedience, righteousness for corruption. When a nation turns away from what brought them Allah's favor, they bring about their own downfall. Conversely, if people change themselves for the better, Allah changes their condition for the better. The starting point of change is always within humans themselves.",
    "And if it is Allah's Will to torment a people, it can never be averted": "Once Allah decides to punish a people for their persistence in wrongdoing, nothing can stop it. No power, no wealth, no army, no strategy can prevent what Allah has decreed. When previous nations reached the point of no return in their rebellion, their destruction came and nothing could save them.",
    "nor can they find a protector other than Him": "Besides Allah, there is no one who can protect them from His punishment or help them against His decree. All the so-called protectors and helpers they relied upon will be useless when Allah's judgment comes. This emphasizes complete dependence on Allah and the futility of seeking protection from any other source."
  },
  12: {
    "He is the One Who shows you lightning, inspiring ˹you with˺ hope and fear": "Allah displays lightning as a sign of His power. Lightning inspires both hope and fear simultaneously—hope because it signals coming rain that will bring life to the earth and provide water for crops and drinking; fear because it can strike and cause destruction, fires, and death. This dual nature reminds humans of Allah's ability to give life and cause death, to bless and to punish.",
    "and produces heavy clouds": "Allah creates the massive clouds that are laden with water, hanging heavy in the sky. These clouds, which can weigh billions of tons yet float in the air, are another demonstration of Allah's power over creation. He forms them, moves them, and causes them to release their rain wherever and whenever He wills."
  },
  13: {
    "The thunder glorifies His praises": "The thunder, which we hear as a loud sound during storms, is in fact glorifying and praising Allah. Everything in creation worships Allah in its own way, even phenomena we might consider mere natural occurrences. The Prophet (peace be upon him) used to say when hearing thunder: \"Glory be to Him Whom the thunder glorifies with His praise, and the angels too, out of fear of Him.\"",
    "as do the angels in awe of Him": "The angels, despite their purity, closeness to Allah, and constant worship, are in a state of awe and reverential fear of Allah. If such noble and obedient beings fear Allah, how much more should humans—who are weak and sinful—fear and revere their Lord?",
    "He sends thunderbolts, striking with them whoever He wills": "Allah sends lightning strikes that can destroy whatever He wills. These thunderbolts are under His complete control, hitting exactly what He intends. This is a demonstration of His power and a warning to those who defy Him. Historical accounts mention people who challenged Allah being struck by lightning.",
    "Yet they dispute about Allah. And He is tremendous in might": "Despite all these overwhelming displays of power—the lightning, thunder, rain, and storms—some people still argue and dispute about Allah. They question His existence, His oneness, His ability, or His right to be worshipped alone. How foolish to dispute about the One who demonstrates such tremendous power! He is mighty in His plan and severe in His punishment against those who oppose Him."
  },
  14: {
    "Calling upon Him ˹alone˺ is the truth": "The only true and valid supplication is the one directed to Allah alone. He alone hears all prayers, has power over all things, and can respond to any request. Prayer to Allah is based on truth and reality—He exists, He hears, He has power, and He responds. This is the only call that makes sense.",
    "But those ˹idols˺ the pagans invoke besides Him ˹can˺ never respond to them in any way": "The false gods that people worship besides Allah—whether idols, saints, or any other creation—have no ability whatsoever to respond to those who call upon them. They cannot hear, they cannot act, and they have no power to benefit or harm. The worship directed to them is completely wasted.",
    "˹It is˺ just like someone who stretches out their hands to water, ˹asking it˺ to reach their mouths, but it can never do so": "Allah presents a vivid parable: imagine a thirsty person sitting at a distance from water, stretching out their hands toward it, hoping it will somehow reach their mouth. No matter how long they wait or how desperately they reach, the water will never come to them on its own. This is exactly like the idol worshipper calling out to lifeless gods—the response will never come because it cannot come.",
    "The calls of the disbelievers are only in vain": "The prayers and invocations of those who call upon other than Allah are completely lost and wasted. They gain nothing from their worship, neither in this world nor the hereafter. All that effort, devotion, and hope directed at false gods leads nowhere—it is misguidance upon misguidance."
  },
  15: {
    "To Allah ˹alone˺ bow down ˹in submission˺ all those in the heavens and the earth": "Every being in the heavens and earth prostrates and submits to Allah. The angels, the celestial bodies, the creatures on earth—all are in a state of submission to their Creator. Prostration here includes both the physical act of worship and the broader submission to Allah's will and command.",
    "willingly or unwillingly": "Some submit willingly, like the believers and the angels, who love to worship Allah and find peace in submission. Others submit unwillingly—the disbelievers who deny Allah with their tongues still submit to Him through their very existence. Their bodies follow His laws of nature; they cannot escape His decree of life, death, sickness, and health. Even Pharaoh, who claimed divinity, submitted unwillingly to Allah's laws of creation.",
    "as do their shadows, morning and evening": "Even the shadows of all things prostrate to Allah. As shadows lengthen and shorten, shifting with the movement of the sun from morning to evening, they are in a state of submission and prostration to Allah. This poetic imagery shows that submission to Allah is woven into the very fabric of existence—even something as intangible as a shadow worships its Creator."
  },
  16: {
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Who is the Lord of the heavens and the earth?\" Say, \"Allah!\"": "Allah commands the Prophet to pose this fundamental question to the disbelievers: Who created and sustains the heavens and the earth? Even the polytheists of Makkah would acknowledge that it is Allah who created everything. The answer is undeniable—Allah is the Lord of all that exists.",
    "Ask ˹them˺, \"Why ˹then˺ have you taken besides Him lords who cannot even benefit or protect themselves?\"": "Having established that Allah is the Creator, the logical question follows: why then do you worship others besides Him—beings that cannot even help themselves? These idols, saints, or entities they worship have no power to bring benefit to themselves or ward off harm from themselves. How could they possibly help you?",
    "Say, \"Can the blind and the sighted be equal? Or can darkness and light be equal?\"": "These rhetorical questions highlight the obvious difference between truth and falsehood. Just as a blind person and one who sees cannot be considered equal in ability, and just as darkness and light are opposites that cannot be equated, so too are those who worship Allah alone versus those who associate partners with Him. The believer who sees the truth is nothing like the disbeliever stumbling in darkness.",
    "Or have they associated with Allah partners who ˹supposedly˺ produced a creation like His, leaving them confused between the two creations?": "Is their excuse that these partners they worship also created something, causing them to be confused about who the real Creator is? Of course not. None of their so-called gods created anything at all. There is no competing creation that could cause legitimate confusion. The entire creation testifies to one Creator.",
    "Say, \"Allah is the Creator of all things, and He is the One, the Supreme.\"": "The conclusion is clear and emphatic: Allah alone is the Creator of everything that exists—every atom, every being, every phenomenon. He is One, without partner, without equal, without rival. He is the Supreme, the One who dominates and overpowers all things. There is no god worthy of worship except Him."
  },
  17: {
    "He sends down rain from the sky, causing the valleys to flow, each according to its capacity": "Allah sends rain, and water flows through valleys—some large, some small—each carrying as much as it can handle. A large valley carries more water; a small stream carries less. Similarly, people receive guidance according to their capacity—hearts that are open and large absorb more truth, while hard and restricted hearts receive little.",
    "The currents then carry along rising foam": "As water rushes through valleys, it picks up debris and produces foam that rises to the surface. This foam floats on top, appearing prominent and visible, but it is actually worthless refuse that the water carries.",
    "similar to the slag produced from metal that people melt in the fire for ornaments or tools": "Allah gives another example: when people smelt gold, silver, or other metals to make jewelry or useful tools, impurities rise to the surface as slag or dross. This waste floats on top of the pure metal, just like the foam on water. Both appear prominently but are worthless.",
    "This is how Allah compares truth to falsehood": "The truth is like the pure water that remains and benefits the land, or the pure metal used for beneficial purposes. Falsehood is like the foam or the slag—it may appear large and prominent for a while, rising to the surface and making noise, but it has no substance or lasting value.",
    "The ˹worthless˺ residue is then cast away": "The foam on water eventually dissipates and disappears. The slag is thrown away as waste. Similarly, falsehood—no matter how prominent it may seem temporarily—will inevitably vanish. False ideologies, tyrannical systems, and disbelief may seem powerful for a time, but they are destined to perish.",
    "but what benefits people remains on the earth": "The pure water soaks into the earth, giving life to plants and providing drink for creation. The pure metal is fashioned into useful items. Likewise, truth and beneficial knowledge remain and continue to benefit humanity long after falsehood has been forgotten.",
    "This is how Allah sets forth parables": "Allah uses these vivid, relatable examples from everyday life to make profound truths understandable. Through simple imagery that anyone can observe—rain, water, foam, metal, slag—He explains the nature of truth and falsehood and their ultimate destinies."
  },
  18: {
    "Those who respond to ˹the call of˺ their Lord will have the finest reward": "Those who hear Allah's call through His messengers and revelation, and respond with faith and obedience, will receive the best reward—Paradise and all its blessings. Responding means accepting the truth, following the guidance, and living accordingly. For them is the ultimate good.",
    "As for those who do not respond to Him": "Those who hear the call but reject it, who are presented with truth but turn away, who are invited to guidance but refuse—they face a different fate entirely.",
    "even if they were to possess everything in the world twice over, they would certainly offer it to ransom themselves": "On the Day of Judgment, when they see the punishment awaiting them, they would desperately wish to give everything—all the wealth of the entire earth, and even twice that amount—as ransom to save themselves. But no ransom will be accepted on that Day.",
    "They will face strict judgment": "Their reckoning will be severe, with every sin counted against them and no excuse accepted. Unlike the believers whose minor sins may be overlooked by Allah's mercy, these rejecters will face detailed and harsh accounting.",
    "and Hell will be their home. What an evil place to rest!": "Their final dwelling will be Hell—a terrible resting place. The word 'rest' is used ironically, for there is no rest in Hell, only continuous torment. What a miserable destination for those who rejected the truth!"
  },
  19: {
    "Can the one who knows that your Lord's revelation to you ˹O Prophet˺ is the truth be like the one who is blind?": "This is a rhetorical question with an obvious answer: No! The person who recognizes and accepts that the Quran is the truth from Allah cannot possibly be equal to one who is spiritually blind and rejects it. The believer has sight, insight, and guidance; the disbeliever stumbles in darkness. How could they be the same?",
    "None will be mindful ˹of this˺ except people of reason": "Only those who truly use their intellect—people with sound minds who reflect deeply—will take heed of these lessons. The Quran repeatedly calls upon people of understanding, those who think and reflect, because faith and reason go hand in hand. Those who abandon rational thinking miss the clear signs of truth."
  },
  20: {
    "˹They are˺ those who honour Allah's covenant, never breaking the pledge": "The people of reason are those who fulfill their covenant with Allah—the commitment to believe in Him, worship Him alone, and follow His guidance. When they make a promise to Allah, they keep it. They do not break their word or abandon their commitments, whether with Allah or with people. Keeping covenants is a sign of true faith and integrity."
  },
  21: {
    "and those who maintain whatever ˹ties˺ Allah has ordered to be maintained": "They preserve the connections that Allah has commanded—family ties, relations of kinship, bonds of brotherhood in faith, and the rights of neighbors and community. They do not cut off relatives or sever bonds that Allah has ordered to be maintained. Maintaining these ties is a sign of faith and brings blessings, while cutting them brings Allah's curse.",
    "stand in awe of their Lord": "They have a deep sense of reverence and fear of Allah. This is not a paralyzing terror but a conscious awareness of Allah's greatness and His awareness of all they do. This awe motivates them to obey and prevents them from sinning.",
    "and fear strict judgment": "They are conscious that they will face Allah's judgment, and they fear that their account may be harsh if they fail to live righteously. This fear of the reckoning keeps them on the straight path, careful about their deeds and words."
  },
  22: {
    "And ˹they are˺ those who endure patiently, seeking their Lord's pleasure": "They bear difficulties—whether in worship, in abstaining from sin, or in facing life's hardships—with patience. Their motivation is not to impress people or gain worldly benefits, but solely to seek Allah's face and pleasure. This sincerity transforms their patience into worship.",
    "establish prayer": "They do not merely pray occasionally; they establish the prayer—performing it consistently at its proper times, with proper form, presence of heart, and in congregation when possible. Prayer is the pillar of faith and the connection between servant and Lord.",
    "donate from what We have provided for them—secretly and openly": "They spend in charity from what Allah has given them—sometimes publicly to encourage others and sometimes secretly to protect their sincerity. Both forms of giving are praiseworthy when done with the right intention. They recognize that their wealth is a trust from Allah, not truly theirs.",
    "and respond to evil with good": "When people treat them badly, they do not retaliate in kind. Instead, they respond to harm with goodness, to insults with kindness, to hatred with patience. This noble character transforms enemies into friends and earns Allah's pleasure. The Prophet (peace be upon him) exemplified this throughout his life.",
    "It is they who will have the ultimate abode": "For people with these qualities, the final home—the best outcome in the hereafter—is reserved. Their patience, prayers, charity, and noble character will be rewarded with the eternal bliss of Paradise."
  },
  23: {
    "the Gardens of Eternity, which they will enter": "Their reward is the Gardens of Eden—Paradise, a place of eternal residence where they will live forever. These gardens are characterized by everlasting bliss, with no death, no aging, no sorrow, and no end to the enjoyment.",
    "along with the righteous among their parents, spouses, and descendants": "One of the greatest joys of Paradise is reunion with loved ones. The righteous will be joined by their believing family members—parents, spouses, and children who were also righteous. Even if some family members were at lower levels of Paradise, Allah may elevate them to be together, completing the happiness without diminishing anyone's reward.",
    "And the angels will enter upon them from every gate, ˹saying,˺": "Angels will come to visit and honor them, entering from every door of their palatial homes in Paradise. These angelic visits will bring greetings, congratulations, and further honors, a continual celebration of their achievement."
  },
  24: {
    "\"Peace be upon you for your perseverance": "The angels will greet them with peace—the ultimate state in Paradise where there is no disturbance, fear, or worry. They specifically mention that this reward came because of their patience. All those years of enduring difficulties, resisting temptation, and steadfastly obeying Allah have led to this moment of eternal peace.",
    "How excellent is the ultimate abode!\"": "The angels proclaim how wonderful this final home is—far better than anything they left behind in the worldly life. Every hardship endured, every sacrifice made, every struggle faced was worth it for this magnificent, eternal reward."
  },
  25: {
    "And those who violate Allah's covenant after it has been affirmed": "In contrast to the righteous, these are people who break their covenant with Allah. After knowing the truth and affirming their commitment to follow it, they turn away and violate that sacred agreement. They know what is right but choose to abandon it.",
    "break whatever ˹ties˺ Allah has ordered to be maintained": "They sever the relationships and bonds that Allah commanded them to maintain—cutting off family ties, breaking the brotherhood of faith, abandoning their responsibilities toward relatives and community. While the righteous maintain connections, these people destroy them.",
    "and spread corruption in the land": "They cause mischief and corruption on earth through their disbelief, sins, injustice, and promotion of evil. Instead of contributing positively to society and creation, they spread harm, immorality, and destruction. Their influence is toxic and destructive.",
    "it is they who will be condemned": "Upon them is Allah's curse—being removed far from His mercy. This is the most severe consequence, to be expelled from divine compassion and left to face His wrath.",
    "and will have the worst abode": "Their final dwelling will be the most terrible place—Hell, with all its horrors. Just as the righteous have the best home in Paradise, these wicked ones will have the worst home in Hell. What a stark contrast and what a powerful motivation to choose the path of righteousness!"
  },
  26: {
    "Allah gives abundant or limited provisions to whoever He wills": "Allah alone controls the distribution of wealth and sustenance. He expands provision for some, making them wealthy, and restricts it for others, keeping them with less. This is not random, nor is it based on who deserves more or who is better in Allah's sight. Wealth is a test, not a sign of divine favor. A disbeliever may be rich while a righteous believer may be poor—both are being tested in different ways.",
    "And the disbelievers become prideful of ˹the pleasures of˺ this worldly life": "The disbelievers rejoice arrogantly in their worldly possessions—wealth, status, comfort, and pleasures. They take pride in these temporary blessings, mistakenly thinking that material success indicates they are on the right path or that Allah is pleased with them. This pride blinds them from seeking the truth.",
    "But the life of this world, compared to the Hereafter, is nothing but a fleeting enjoyment": "When compared to the eternal life of the Hereafter, this entire worldly existence—with all its pleasures, achievements, and possessions—is merely a brief, insignificant enjoyment. It is like a traveler stopping briefly at a rest station before continuing to their final destination. The wise person does not become attached to the rest stop; they prepare for the journey ahead."
  },
  27: {
    "The disbelievers say, \"If only a sign could be sent down to him from his Lord.\"": "The disbelievers repeatedly demanded miraculous signs according to their own preferences—perhaps wanting the Prophet to split mountains or perform supernatural feats on command. They used this as an excuse to reject the message, claiming that without such signs, they could not believe. Yet the Quran itself was the greatest sign, and history shows that even those who witnessed miracles often disbelieved anyway.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Indeed, Allah leaves to stray whoever He wills": "Allah responds to their demand by clarifying that guidance is not simply about seeing signs—it is about the heart. Allah allows those who are determined to reject the truth to remain in their misguidance. This is not arbitrary; it is a consequence of their own choice to turn away. Allah does not force anyone into disbelief, but He does not force guidance upon those who refuse it.",
    "and guides to Himself whoever turns to Him": "On the other hand, whoever sincerely turns to Allah seeking guidance, whoever humbles themselves and opens their heart to the truth—Allah guides such a person to Himself. The door of guidance is open to anyone who truly seeks it with a sincere heart. The key is turning to Allah, not demanding signs on one's own terms."
  },
  28: {
    "those who believe and whose hearts find comfort in the remembrance of Allah": "Those who turn to Allah are the believers whose hearts achieve tranquility through remembering Him. When they mention Allah's name, recite His words, reflect on His attributes, and maintain consciousness of Him, their hearts become calm and serene. Anxiety, fear, and restlessness give way to peace and contentment.",
    "Surely in the remembrance of Allah do hearts find comfort": "This is a profound statement of truth. The human heart was created to know and remember Allah, and it cannot find true peace except through this connection. People chase wealth, fame, pleasure, and relationships seeking peace, but true inner tranquility comes only from remembering Allah. This is why the richest and most successful people can be deeply unhappy, while a poor believer who remembers Allah can be completely at peace. The heart finds its rest in its Creator."
  },
  29: {
    "Those who believe and do good": "Faith must be accompanied by righteous action. True believers are those who not only have faith in their hearts but also express it through good deeds—prayer, charity, kindness, honesty, and all forms of obedience to Allah. Belief and action are inseparable in Islam.",
    "for them will be bliss and an honourable destination": "For such believers, there is Tuba—a word that encompasses all forms of goodness, happiness, and blessing. Some scholars say Tuba is a tree in Paradise whose shade extends across the entire garden. Others understand it as comprehensive bliss and joy. Additionally, they will have the best destination—Paradise, the most honorable and beautiful final home one could ever hope for."
  },
  30: {
    "And so We have sent you ˹O Prophet˺ to a community, like ˹We did with˺ earlier communities": "Allah reminds the Prophet that his situation is not unique. Just as Allah sent messengers to previous nations throughout history—to the people of Noah, Abraham, Moses, Jesus, and others—He has now sent Muhammad to his community. The pattern of prophethood continues, and the Prophet is part of a long chain of messengers.",
    "so that you may recite to them what We have revealed to you": "The Prophet's primary duty is to convey the revelation—the Quran—to his people. He recites to them the divine words that Allah has revealed, delivering the message clearly and faithfully. This is the mission: to communicate Allah's guidance to humanity.",
    "Yet they deny the Most Compassionate": "Despite this clear guidance, they reject Ar-Rahman—the Most Compassionate. Some of the polytheists of Makkah claimed not to know who Ar-Rahman was, rejecting this name of Allah. This denial of Allah's name is essentially denial of Allah Himself. They reject the very source of all mercy and compassion.",
    "Say, \"He is my Lord! There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him": "The Prophet is instructed to respond with a clear declaration of faith. Ar-Rahman is his Lord, the only true deity worthy of worship. This statement of Tawheed (monotheism) is the foundation of the entire message. There is no god but Allah.",
    "In Him I put my trust, and to Him I turn ˹in repentance˺": "The Prophet demonstrates complete reliance on Allah—trusting Him for protection, provision, and success in his mission. He also turns to Allah in repentance, showing that even the Prophet, the best of creation, constantly seeks Allah's forgiveness and returns to Him. This models the believer's relationship with Allah: trust and repentance."
  },
  31: {
    "If there were a recitation that could cause mountains to move, or the earth to split, or the dead to speak, ˹it would have been this Quran˺": "If any scripture had the power to physically move mountains, crack the earth open, or make the dead rise and speak, it would be this Quran. This highlights the Quran's supreme status and power. Yet the point is that even such miraculous displays would not convince those determined to disbelieve. The problem is not lack of evidence; it is hardness of hearts.",
    "But all matters are by Allah's Will": "Ultimately, everything—including guidance and misguidance, miracles and their effects—is under Allah's control and happens according to His will. He decides what signs to show and whom to guide.",
    "Have the believers not yet realized that had Allah willed, He could have guided all of humanity?": "The believers should understand that if Allah had willed, He could have made every single person a believer. But He chose to give humans free will and to test them. Forced guidance would defeat the purpose of the test of life. Allah's wisdom is in allowing people to choose.",
    "And disasters will continue to afflict the disbelievers or strike close to their homes for their misdeeds, until Allah's promise comes to pass": "The disbelievers will continue to face calamities and hardships—natural disasters, military defeats, loss of territory—as consequences of their rejection of truth. These troubles will strike them directly or occur nearby as warnings. This will continue until Allah's final promise (the Day of Judgment or the conquest of Makkah) arrives.",
    "Surely Allah never fails in His promise": "Whatever Allah has promised—punishment for the disbelievers, victory for the believers, the coming of the Day of Judgment—will definitely occur. Allah's promises are absolutely certain; there is no possibility of failure or change."
  },
  32: {
    "Other messengers had already been ridiculed before you": "The Prophet is being comforted here. He is not the first messenger to be mocked and rejected. Previous prophets faced the same ridicule from their people. This is the pattern throughout history—disbelievers mock those who bring them truth. The Prophet should not be discouraged; he is in noble company.",
    "but I delayed the disbelievers ˹for a while˺ then seized them": "Allah gave those previous nations time—perhaps they would repent, perhaps they would realize their error. This delay was mercy and opportunity. But when they persisted in their mockery and rejection, Allah eventually seized them with punishment. The delay should not be mistaken for inability or approval.",
    "And how ˹horrible˺ was My punishment!": "The punishment that finally came upon them was severe and terrifying. The people of Noah were drowned, the people of Lot were destroyed with stones, Pharaoh's army was swallowed by the sea. These historical examples serve as warnings. How terrible was the consequence of mocking Allah's messengers!"
  },
  33: {
    "Is ˹there any equal to˺ the Vigilant One Who knows what every soul commits?": "Allah is the One who watches over every soul and knows exactly what each person earns through their deeds. He is fully aware of every action, intention, and secret. Can anyone or anything else have this complete, comprehensive knowledge and watchfulness? Obviously not. How then can they compare others to Him?",
    "Yet the pagans have associated others with Allah ˹in worship˺": "Despite Allah's unique and unmatched qualities, the polytheists have set up partners with Him—idols, beings, or entities they worship alongside or instead of Allah. This is the height of irrationality.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Name them!": "Challenge them to identify these so-called partners. Who are they? What are their names? What have they created? What power do they have? The challenge exposes the emptiness of their claim.",
    "Or do you ˹mean to˺ inform Him of something He does not know on the earth?": "This is a rhetorical question with biting irony. Are they suggesting there are gods on earth that Allah does not know about? Allah, who knows everything seen and unseen, has not acknowledged any such partners. So are they informing Allah of something He missed? The absurdity is clear.",
    "Or are these ˹gods˺ just empty words?\"": "Perhaps these 'gods' are nothing but names without substance—empty words with no reality behind them. People have invented names and attributed divinity to things that have no real power or existence as gods.",
    "In fact, the disbelievers' falsehood has been made so appealing to them that they have been turned away from the Path": "The reality is that their false beliefs have been beautified in their eyes. Whether through Satan's whispering, their own desires, or social conditioning, their misguidance appears attractive to them. This beautification has caused them to be blocked from the straight path.",
    "And whoever Allah leaves to stray will be left with no guide": "When someone persists in rejecting truth until Allah allows them to remain in misguidance, no one can guide them. No prophet, no scripture, no argument can help someone whom Allah has left astray due to their own stubborn rejection."
  },
  34: {
    "For them is punishment in this worldly life": "The disbelievers will face punishment even in this world—humiliation, defeat, loss, disasters, and various forms of suffering. They do not escape consequences simply because the Day of Judgment has not yet arrived.",
    "but the punishment of the Hereafter is truly far worse": "As terrible as worldly punishment may be, it is nothing compared to the punishment of the Hereafter. The torment of Hell is more severe, more lasting, and more painful than anything experienced in this temporary life. This should terrify anyone who reflects on it.",
    "And none can shield them from Allah": "When Allah's punishment comes, no one and nothing can protect them from it. No wealth, no power, no allies, no hiding place can shield them from the Lord of all creation. They are completely helpless before His decree."
  },
  35: {
    "The description of the Paradise promised to the righteous is that under it rivers flow": "Allah describes the Paradise awaiting the God-conscious believers. Beneath its gardens, palaces, and trees flow rivers—rivers of water, milk, honey, and wine that brings no intoxication. These rivers flow continuously, providing beauty, sustenance, and endless delight to the inhabitants of Paradise.",
    "eternal is its fruit as well as its shade": "Unlike worldly fruit that is seasonal and perishable, the fruits of Paradise never end. They are always available, always fresh, always abundant. Similarly, its shade never diminishes—there is no harsh sun or discomfort. Everything in Paradise is permanent and perfect.",
    "That is the ˹ultimate˺ outcome for the righteous": "This is the final destination for those who lived righteously, who feared Allah and obeyed Him. After the struggles and tests of worldly life, they arrive at this eternal home of bliss. What a reward for their patience and faith!",
    "But the outcome for the disbelievers is the Fire!": "In stark contrast, the final destination for those who rejected faith is Hell—the Fire. While the righteous enjoy eternal gardens with flowing rivers, the disbelievers suffer in flames. The difference could not be more extreme. Each person chooses their path and therefore their destination."
  },
  36: {
    "˹The believers among˺ those who were given the Scripture rejoice at what has been revealed to you ˹O Prophet˺": "Those among the Jews and Christians who recognized the truth and believed were delighted when the Quran was revealed. They saw it as confirmation of what their own scriptures had foretold. Sincere seekers of truth from the People of the Book recognized the Prophet and rejoiced at his message.",
    "while some ˹disbelieving˺ factions deny a portion of it": "However, other groups among them rejected parts of the Quran. They might accept some portions that agreed with their existing beliefs while denying other parts. This selective rejection shows their insincerity—true acceptance of divine guidance means accepting it completely, not picking and choosing.",
    "Say, \"I have only been commanded to worship Allah, associating none with Him ˹in worship˺": "The Prophet's response is simple and clear: his mission is to worship Allah alone without any partners. This is the essence of the message, the same message brought by all previous prophets. Whether people accept all of it, part of it, or none of it, this is what he has been commanded to do.",
    "To Him I invite ˹all˺, and to Him is my return\"": "The Prophet invites everyone to Allah—not to himself, not to a tribe or nation, but to the Creator. And his own final return is to Allah. Both the call and the destination are focused entirely on Allah."
  },
  37: {
    "And so We have revealed it as an authority in Arabic": "Allah revealed the Quran in Arabic, giving it the authority to judge and guide. Arabic was the language of the Prophet and his people, making the message clear and undeniable to them. The Quran serves as the criterion for truth, the final authority in matters of religion.",
    "And if you were to follow their desires after ˹all˺ the knowledge that has come to you": "This is a stern warning, even to the Prophet himself. If he were to abandon the clear knowledge of revelation and instead follow the wishes and desires of those who reject or partially accept the truth, there would be serious consequences. This warning applies even more strongly to ordinary believers.",
    "there would be none to protect or shield you from Allah": "No one could protect or help anyone who abandons divine guidance to follow human desires. Once a person knowingly turns from truth to please others, they lose Allah's protection. This emphasizes that no compromise is acceptable when it comes to the fundamentals of faith."
  },
  38: {
    "We have certainly sent messengers before you ˹O Prophet˺ and blessed them with wives and offspring": "Previous prophets were human beings with normal human lives—they married, had children, and lived among their people. This addresses those who criticized the Prophet for having wives and family, as if a messenger should be superhuman. Prophets are humans chosen to deliver Allah's message; their humanity does not diminish their prophethood.",
    "It was not for any messenger to bring a sign without Allah's permission": "No messenger could produce miracles on his own or on demand. Miracles are by Allah's will and permission, not subject to human control—even the control of prophets. When the disbelievers demanded specific signs, they misunderstood the nature of prophethood. Prophets deliver messages; Allah decides when and what signs to show.",
    "Every destined matter has a ˹set˺ time": "Everything that is written and decreed by Allah has its appointed time. Events unfold according to Allah's schedule, not human demands. This includes the timing of miracles, punishments, victories, and all other matters. Patience is required, for everything will come at its proper time."
  },
  39: {
    "Allah eliminates and confirms what He wills": "Allah has absolute authority to erase, cancel, change, or confirm whatever He wills. Some scholars explain this refers to abrogation in legislation, others to the changing of decree based on one's deeds (such as supplication changing destiny), and others to the recording of deeds by angels that Allah may alter. Allah's will is supreme in all matters.",
    "and with Him is the Master Record": "With Allah is the Umm al-Kitab—the Mother of the Book, the Preserved Tablet (Lawh al-Mahfuz) where everything is recorded. This is the original, unchanging record of all that was, is, and will be. While certain things may change in the records held by angels, the Master Record with Allah contains the final, absolute truth of all matters."
  },
  40: {
    "Whether We show you ˹O Prophet˺ some of what We threaten them with, or cause you to die ˹before that˺": "Allah may allow the Prophet to witness the punishment and defeat of the disbelievers during his lifetime, or the Prophet may pass away before that happens. Either way, the outcome is in Allah's hands.",
    "your duty is only to deliver ˹the message˺": "The Prophet's responsibility is clear and limited: to convey the message faithfully and completely. He is not responsible for making people believe, nor for bringing about their punishment. His job is delivery; the results are up to Allah. This brings comfort—success is in fulfilling one's duty, not in controlling outcomes.",
    "Judgment is for Us": "Allah alone judges and holds people accountable. The Prophet does not judge them; Allah does. This division of roles is important: prophets deliver, Allah judges. Believers convey truth, Allah guides. This removes the burden of outcomes from human shoulders and places it where it belongs—with Allah."
  },
  41: {
    "Do they not see that We gradually reduce their land from its borders?": "Allah draws attention to a visible sign: the land controlled by the disbelievers is being reduced from its edges. This could refer to the Muslims gaining territory, the deaths of their leaders and scholars, or the general decline of their power. The disbelievers should observe these signs and realize that their dominance is not permanent.",
    "Allah decides—none can reverse His decision": "When Allah makes a judgment or decree, no one can overturn it, appeal it, or change it. His decisions are final and absolute. No power in the heavens or earth can challenge what Allah has determined.",
    "And He is swift in reckoning": "Allah's accounting is fast. When the time comes for judgment, whether in this life or the next, it happens quickly. Allah does not need time to calculate or deliberate—His knowledge is complete and His judgment is instant."
  },
  42: {
    "Those ˹disbelievers˺ before them ˹secretly˺ planned": "Previous nations also plotted and schemed against Allah's messengers and His religion. They made secret plans to undermine the truth, thinking their conspiracies would succeed.",
    "but Allah has the ultimate plan": "All planning belongs to Allah. He knows every secret plot and has the power to counter it. Human scheming, no matter how clever, is nothing compared to Allah's plan. He turns their plots against them and brings His will to pass regardless of their efforts.",
    "He knows what every soul commits": "Allah is fully aware of every deed, intention, and secret plan of every soul. Nothing is hidden from Him. This complete knowledge means no plot escapes His awareness, and no scheme can succeed against His will.",
    "And the disbelievers will soon know who will have the ultimate outcome": "The disbelievers will eventually discover—whether in this life or definitively in the Hereafter—who truly succeeds in the end. They may seem powerful now, but the final victory belongs to the believers. The ultimate outcome, the best final home, is for those who believed and obeyed Allah."
  },
  43: {
    "The disbelievers say, \"You ˹Muḥammad˺ are no messenger.\"": "The disbelievers flatly denied the Prophet's prophethood, claiming he was not sent by Allah. This direct rejection was their attempt to dismiss the entire message by denying its source. If he is not a messenger, they reasoned, then his message can be ignored.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Allah is sufficient as a Witness between me and you": "The Prophet is instructed to respond that Allah Himself is witness to his truthfulness. Allah knows who is truly His messenger and who is lying. On the Day of Judgment, this witness will be made manifest. Allah's testimony is the most powerful and sufficient witness anyone could have.",
    "as is whoever has knowledge of the Scripture\"": "Additionally, those who have true knowledge of previous scriptures—the Torah and the Gospel—can recognize the signs of prophethood in Muhammad. The sincere scholars among the People of the Book who knew their scriptures well could confirm that the Prophet matched the descriptions of the awaited messenger. Their testimony joins Allah's testimony as witness to the Prophet's truthfulness."
  }
};